 a tattoo gun, the conversion narrative has been redefined by some authors for subversive purposes, including questioning the ostensible emancipatory role of prison writing, critiquing white supremacy, and broadly reimagining autobiographical discourse. An interdisciplinary work that brings life writing scholarship into conversation with prison studies and law and literature studies, Prison Life Writing theorizes how life writing works in prison, explains literature’s complicated entanglements with institutional power, and demonstrates the political and aesthetic innovations of one of America’s most fascinating literary genres.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConversion in literature. 0aPrisoners in literature. 0aPrisonerszUnited StatesxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aPrisoners' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aPrisons in literature. 0aPrisonszUnited States. 4aLife Writing. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a.  aAfrican American Literature.  aAmerican Literature.  aAmerican Studies.  aAssata Shakur.  aAutobiography.  aCarl Panzram.  aChicano Literature.  aConversion Narrative.  aCriminal Justice.  aCriminology.  aCritical Race Theory.  aGender Studies.  aGeorge Jackson.  aJack Henry Abbott.  aJames Carr.  aJimmy Santiago Baca.  aMass Incarceration.  aMemoir.  aPrison Life Writing.  aPrison Literature.  aPrison Resistance Movement.  aRace.  aResistance Literature.  aSexuality.  aShakha Senghor.  aSociology.  aSusan Burton.  aSusan Rosenberg.  aThe New Jim Crow.  aThe U.S. Prison System.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540